Ford GoBike Data Exploration¶

by Ayush Mathur¶

Introduction¶

A bike-share system is a service in which bicycles are made available for shared use to individuals on a short term basis for a price or free. Many bike share systems allow people to borrow a bike from a "dock" and return it at another dock belonging to the same system. Ford GoBike is a public bicycle sharing system in San Francisco Bay Area, California. currently has over 2,600 bicycles in 262 stations across San Francisco, East Bay and San Jose. As of January 2018, the system had seen nearly 500,000 rides since the launch in 2017 and had about 10,000 annual subscribers.

Preliminary Wrangling¶

In this project, we are analyzing data from 2017 to July 2019.

File for data of 2017 is in csv format while the rest of the files are in csv format but zipped. Therefore, we are downloading them seperately. Here, I have created a folder 'extracted_csvs' which will contain all the downloaded files.

Define¶

  • calculate the distance for each ride entry.

We can either use Haversine or Vincenty Formula to calculate distance between two points using Latitude and Longitude. Haversine is simpler but Vincenty is more accurate. Vincenty is more computational intense. Here, I have used Haversine Formula to calculate distance.

Code¶

In [51]:
def cal_dist(lat1,lon1,lat2,lon2):
    r = 6378.1       # Radius of Earth in Km.
    lat1 = radians(lat1)
    lat2 = radians(lat2)
    lon1 = radians(lon1)
    lon2 = radians(lon2)
    
    dlat = lat2 - lat1
    dlon = lon2 - lon1
    
    a = sin(dlat/2)**2 + cos(lat1) * cos(lat2) * sin(dlon/2)**2
    c = 2 * atan2(sqrt(a), sqrt(1-a))
    
    return (r*c)
In [52]:
df_bike_copy['distance'] = df_bike_copy.apply(lambda x: cal_dist(x['start_station_latitude'], x['start_station_longitude'],
                                                       x['end_station_latitude'], x['end_station_longitude']), axis = 1)

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The Dataset contains more than 38.5 Million entries for public bike sharing system Ford GoBike. These entries are anonymous and contain various details about the trip in a total of 26 columns. These details include

  • The Bike id
  • The start and end station ids with latitude and longitude. I used this information to calculate distance and average speed of trip.
  • Duration of the trip
  • Member gender and birth year. Member age was calculated using this.
  • Start and the end time of trip. I created multiple columns for the start/end month, weekday, day of month and hour of the day.

The dataset has been a mix of information previously provided and the additional information extracted.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

The main features of interest are the months, weekdays and time of the day of high demand. How other factors like the age and gender of user affect them. Number of random users compared to the subscribers.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

The distance and duration of trip will help get an insight. Member age shall also play an important role.

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

There are some specific patterns in the usage of Ford Gobike. There is quite a contrast when it comes to Summer v/s winter and Weekdays v/s Weekends. Demand timimgs seem to be affected by the office hours. There are outliers in the duration of the trip. Most of the users are fairly young.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

There were entries with users aged upto 140 years. Users with age above 60 consisted for only about 2.7% of the data. Majority of the rides are for shorter distances and duration. Entries with user age above 60 are dropped. Bikes are kept for long duration but the distance travlled is less. There are entries with incorrect latitude and longitude values for start or end stations. These entries are dropped. Most of the trips are less than an hour long.
